      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>August Derleth (1909-1971) was an American anthologist, publisher and author from Sauk City, Wisconsin.  Best known for being the first publisher of  the works of H.P. Lovecraft, under his Arkham House imprint, Derleth also wrote more than 150 books in many genres, including  history, historical fiction, mysteries, science fiction and more.  His <emph render="italic">Sac Prairie Saga</emph> is a sprawling multi-genre exploration of life in his native Wisconsin.  The August Derleth Society was formed in 1977, "to promote and preserve his memory."</p>
		<p>Nelson Bond (1908-2006) was a Canadian-American author and an early writer of science fiction and fantasy.  In addition to his many short stories, which were published primarily in pulp magazines such as <emph render="italic">Blue Book</emph>, he also wrote for radio, television and the stage.</p>
		</bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">August Derleth Collection</emph> consists of August Derleth Society material, correspondence, memorabilia and miscellany.</p><p>The <emph render="bold">August Derleth Society</emph> material comprises a complete run of the Society's newsletter, from Vol. 1, no. 1 to Vol. 16, no. 4.  The volumes are undated until 1994 (Volume 15), so the date range is uncertain.  Assuming the newsletters were published continuously, that would date the first issue of Volume 1 to 1980.  The Society material also includes a small amount of correspondence with its members and a few printed items such as fliers, brochures, membership postcard, etc.</p><p><emph render="bold">Correspondence</emph> consists entirely of letters between Derleth and author Nelson  Bond.  Much of it relates to Arkham House's publication of Bond's short stories in various anthologies, but the men were also friends and colleagues so there is a good deal of personal conversation as well.   The letters highlight both men's humor and skill with words.</p><p><emph render="bold">Memorabilia</emph> contains a letter from Roderic Meng to Arkham House patrons regarding Derleth's death, a printed flyer listing Derleth's books with a photograph of Derleth and his children on the front, and a large publicity piece from the State Historical Society of Wisconsin for a 1992 program entitled "Wisconsin in His Bones: Remembering August Derleth."</p><p>A small amount of <emph render="bold">Miscellany</emph> completes the collection: several Arkham House book lists published by the company, and a typed list of Bond stories that appeared in anthologies edited by Derleth.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
